Observation Details: Woohoo! After scanning the second pond south of the Unit 1 parking for about 10 minutes, we spotted a Stilt Sandpiper in the northeast corner, at about (33.0799871, -115.7104158). It gave us excellent prolonged looks as it foraged, mixing more with the dowitchers and ibises than with the peeps. Much larger than Western Sandpipers; slightly taller than dowitchers, but slimmer and smaller overall. Bill long and ever so slightly decurved, but shorter than dowitcher bills. Long, yellow legs. Overall, very gray with no brownish tones. Whenever the Stilt Sandpiper bent over to forage, we noted the primaries and tertials were very ruffled, giving it an almost hedgehog-like appearance, making it easy to pick out from among the dowitchers. Photos to be uploaded.

Continuing among Western Sandpipers in the southwest corner of Pond 23. First seen around 9:30 am, on the far, low patch of mud at (32.5919947, -117.1140087). Then, it flew to “stint island”, where it first foraged on the low side of the island at (32.5913097, -117.1132889), and then continued foraging behind the mounds on the right side of the island, out of sight from the viewing platform. The stint stood out readily from the Western Sandpipers next to it. The key field marks we all noted, relative to WESA: a scalier, browner back, a much shorter, slightly decurved bill, and smaller size overall. The legs were black, seen in good lighting from multiple angles. In the scope and binoculars, we could not clearly discern the distinctive facial pattern with the split supercilium, which troubled us, until we took photos that clearly showed the same facial pattern as the Little Stint. Photos attached.

Observation Details: Continuing. Seen at around 9:20am at (37.3926977, -121.9534326). We were looking at a Western Bluebird perched on the lightpost when we heard a clear, loud and sharp call coming from the tree beside us. We saw the Painted Redstart hopping between branches in the tree. In flight, the bird appeared mostly black with red flashes. Once it landed, we clearly saw the large white wingbars, black body, and red belly. The bird remained moving around in the tree for about a minute or two before we lost it. We continued searching but weren't able to refind it. Photos attached.

Observation Details: Continuing, amazing find yesterday by Meg Barron and Ellyn Corey. Refound today by Richard Jeffers at around 4 pm in the oak at (37.3926426, -121.9534172), and the group of 20 or so birders assembled by the eucalyptus where the redstart had previously been seen all sprinted over. We got great looks as it foraged, twisting and turning and hanging upside down from the big branches of the oak - it seemed to favor these branches over thinner branches and leaves. Then, several minutes later, it disappeared and nobody could refind it for the next two hours, despite much effort. Stunning bird, with red breast, black back and head, and white wing patch and outer tail feathers. Tristan might have some identifiable photos, but I just got its tail poking out from behind a branch.

Tristan and I saw an empid low in the big euc, and I passed it off as a Pac-slope until I saw Tristan’s photos - they showed a rather grayish flycatcher with a short, narrow bill, long primary projections, and a short tail. It turned out Carter G. and Steve R. were also looking at this bird at the same time, and looking at Tristan’s photos we all thought it looked very likely to be a Hammond’s. Later, Steve R. got better looks at the flycatcher and was able to confirm it was a Hammond’s, but when everybody else came around the bird flew high up into the euc and was seen only a few more times. Tristan has good photos from when it was low in the euc.

Active in the big Eucalyptus tree at 37.392035, -121.954177 with numerous other Yellow Warbers, Yellow-rumped Warbler, and Western Tanagers. Interesting overall coloration led me to take a picture and after some photo review, it was determined to be Chestnut-sided. Photos attached.

Sergey Pavlov, Tristan Yoo, and I were walking by the pond and ran into Melissa, who told us about the rail. Scanning the pond, I saw the VIRGINIA RAIL on the right side of the pond, directly behind a horizontal line of shorter grass, in the shadow of the reeds. Sergey and Melissa confirmed this sighting.   I was worried that Tristan would miss it but he also saw it once it came back out. We stayed and watched it for about 5 minutes, during which a SORA walked out and went behind the grass, right beside the rail.

Observation Details: Continuing. Seen in the channel on the right side of the trail, specifically, to the east of the east pond, about 3/4 of the way from the trailhead to the north bend of the pond. We saw the bird near a large flock of Mallards, but we were able to identify the Brant by the black head, slightly larger size than Mallard, brown body, and larger white rump. We observed the bird swimming back and forth with the Mallards in the channel for about 10 minutes before deciding to move on.
